          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  If we glue two affine schemes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X,Y]]></fr:tex> together along some standard opens <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \subseteq  X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V \subseteq  Y]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \cong  V]]></fr:tex>, then the union <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \cup  Y]]></fr:tex> is again affine.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y \cong  \operatorname {Spec} E]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V = q]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in  E]]></fr:tex>, with an isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u : D/p \cong  E/q]]></fr:tex>. This way, the global section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \cup  Y]]></fr:tex> by the sheaf condition is given by the following pullback,
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="940ab8df8c57cd772794c8593181cc5c"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/940ab8df8c57cd772794c8593181cc5c.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {tikzcd}
      A \ar [r, "f"] \ar [d, "g"'] \ar [dr, "\lrcorner "{anchor = center, pos = 0.125}, draw = none] & D \ar [d] \\ 
      E \ar [r] & E/q \cong  D/p
    \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  We show that the map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : A \to  D]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \to  A/(q,1)]]></fr:tex>. First since by construction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(q,1) = 1]]></fr:tex>, there is a factorisation
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="5280ab813e963119a541d29f54f4efbf"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/5280ab813e963119a541d29f54f4efbf.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {tikzcd}
      A \ar [r, "f"] \ar [d, two heads] & D \\ 
      A/(q,1) \ar [ur, dashed, "f"']
    \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : A/(q,1) \to  D]]></fr:tex> must be surjective: For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d\in  D]]></fr:tex>, along the isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u D/p \cong  E/q]]></fr:tex> we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(u(d\wedge  p),d) \in  A]]></fr:tex>, whose image under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex>. On the other hand, it must also be injective: For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(e,d),(e',d')\in  A/(q,1)]]></fr:tex>, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d = d']]></fr:tex>. By construction, we must then have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ud = e]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ud' = e']]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e = e']]></fr:tex>. Hence, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(e,d) = (e',d')]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/(q,1)]]></fr:tex>. Similarly, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : A \to  E]]></fr:tex> will be isomorphic to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \to  A/(1,p)]]></fr:tex>.

  This way, by <fr:link href="/schm-X3M9/" title="Universal property of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-X3M9/" display-uri="schm-X3M9" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-X3M9/" display-uri="schm-X3M9" /></fr:link> we get a canonical function
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ X \cup  Y \to  \operatorname {Spec} A ]]></fr:tex>
  We show this is an isomorphism. It suffices to show it is a homeomorphism of topological spaces, because the sheaves are glued together. But this is the same as stating prime filters in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> are either prime filters in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>, modulo the identification. This follows from <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-FMRA/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-FMRA</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-FMRA/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Closed subspace of closed quotient">Closed subspace of closed quotient</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Dually, for an ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, let us write the quotient obtained by taking all elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  \operatorname {Spec} I/D]]></fr:tex>. By the dual form of <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link>, again we have a natural subspace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} I/D \subseteq  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, which can be seen as 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} I/D = \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \forall  a \in  I.\  x \not \models  a\} = \bigcap _{a\in  I}C_a = C_I. ]]></fr:tex>
  Thus, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} I/D]]></fr:tex> will indeed be <html:em>closed</html:em> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, hence we refer to quotients of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I/D]]></fr:tex> as <html:em>closed quotients</html:em>. This also implies that a subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is closed iff it is downward closed.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-EV8L/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-EV8L</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-EV8L/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Quotient of prime filters are local">Quotient of prime filters are local</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any filter <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on a distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/F]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/idem-comm-75C1/" title="Local distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-75C1/" display-uri="idem-comm-75C1" type="local">local</fr:link> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is prime; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/F]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is maximal.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  By <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link>, the inverse image of the quotient <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \twoheadrightarrow  D/F]]></fr:tex> gives a one-to-one correspondence between prime filters in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/F]]></fr:tex> and prime filters containing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/F]]></fr:tex> is local iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{1\}]]></fr:tex> is prime, in which case <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> must be prime. The case for maximality follows from the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> is the only distributive lattice with only one prime filter.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-QVV9/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-QVV9</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-QVV9/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Subspace of pro-open quotients">Subspace of pro-open quotients</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  For a filter <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, via <fr:link href="/idem-comm-W57Q/" title="Prime ideals of pro-open quotient" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-W57Q/" display-uri="idem-comm-W57Q" /></fr:link> the spectrum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/F]]></fr:tex> can be naturally seen as a subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, which is given by 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} D/F = \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \forall  a \in  F.\  x \models  a\} = \bigcap _{a\in  F}O_a, ]]></fr:tex>
  This subspace will be <html:em>upward closed</html:em>, but in general may <html:em>fail</html:em> to be open in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, since it is an infinite intersection of basic opens. This is the reason why we call quotients of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  D/F]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/idem-comm-0002/" title="Pro-open quotients" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-0002/" display-uri="idem-comm-0002" type="local">pro-open</fr:link>, rather than <html:em>open</html:em>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
